    <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
    <p>The Keychron K8 and the Keychron Q1 are two of the most popular mechanical keyboards for people who want more than a generic membrane board, and they sit at very different points on the enthusiast spectrum. The K8, Keychron's wireless tenkeyless keyboard, is the gateway product that introduced countless Mac and Windows users to mechanical typing with its Bluetooth connectivity, hot-swap option, and approachable $99 price. The Q1, Keychron's first custom keyboard, is a serious enthusiast board built around a CNC-machined aluminum body, a gasket-mounted plate, and full QMK/VIA programmability.</p>

    <p>Though both carry the Keychron name and share a tenkeyless layout, they are engineered for different buyers. The K8 is designed for convenience and broad compatibility: it connects over Bluetooth to three devices simultaneously, ships with Mac and Windows keycaps, and offers a hot-swap variant for users who want to try different switches without soldering. The Q1 is designed for typing feel and customization: its heavy aluminum case, gasket mount, and sound-dampening foam produce a noticeably more refined typing experience, and its QMK/VIA support lets you remap every key and program layers.</p>

    <p>The trade-off is connectivity and price. The K8 is wireless and costs $99; the Q1 is wired-only and costs $149. For buyers deciding between them, the question is whether the Q1's premium build and typing feel are worth giving up Bluetooth and spending $50 more. After using both keyboards for months of daily typing, coding, and general productivity, here is the detailed comparison.</p>

