    <h2 id="pros-cons">Pros and Cons</h2>
    <h3>Keychron K8</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>✓ Wireless Bluetooth with 3-device multipoint switching</li>
      <li>✓ Affordable $99 entry point into mechanical keyboards</li>
      <li>✓ Mac-friendly with included Mac keycaps and layout toggle</li>
      <li>✓ Hot-swap variant available for switch experimentation</li>
      <li>✓ Compact tenkeyless size fits smaller desks</li>
      <li>✗ Plastic body feels less premium and is less acoustically dead</li>
      <li>✗ Tray-mount typing feel is firmer and more hollow-sounding</li>
      <li>✗ No QMK/VIA programmability for custom layouts</li>
      <li>✗ No gasket mount or sound-dampening foam</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Keychron Q1</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>✓ Premium CNC aluminum body with excellent build quality</li>
      <li>✓ Gasket-mounted plate delivers a softer, cushioned typing feel</li>
      <li>✓ Full QMK/VIA support for per-key remapping and layers</li>
      <li>✓ Hot-swap sockets standard across all variants</li>
      <li>✓ Sound-dampening foam produces a deeper, thockier sound</li>
      <li>✗ Wired-only, no Bluetooth connectivity</li>
      <li>✗ $149 price is $50 more than the K8</li>
      <li>✗ Heavier aluminum body is less portable</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="performance">Performance</h2>
    <p>Typing feel is where the Keychron Q1 establishes its enthusiast credentials. The Q1 uses a gasket-mounted plate, meaning the plate that holds the switches is suspended between cushioning pads rather than screwed rigidly to the case. This allows the plate to flex slightly with each keystroke, producing a softer, more forgiving bottom-out feel that enthusiasts describe as bouncy or cushioned. Combined with the sound-dampening foam inside the heavy aluminum case, the Q1 produces a deep, thocky sound profile that is a noticeable step up from the K8's firmer, more plasticky report. For anyone who has used a generic mechanical keyboard and wondered what the enthusiast fuss is about, the Q1 makes the difference immediately obvious.</p>

    <p>The Keychron K8 is a competent typist for its price, but its tray-mount design — where the plate is screwed directly to the case at several points — produces a firmer, more rigid bottom-out with a hollower sound. This is not bad; many users prefer the crisp, defined feedback of a tray-mount board, and the K8's Gateron switches are reliable and pleasant. But the K8 cannot match the Q1's refined acoustic and tactile experience, and its plastic case transmits more vibration into the desk. For long typing sessions, most users will find the Q1 less fatiguing and more satisfying, though the K8 is perfectly adequate for casual and productivity use.</p>

    <p>Connectivity is the K8's defining advantage. Its Bluetooth 5.1 radio pairs with up to three devices simultaneously and switches between them with a key combination, which is invaluable for users who work across a laptop, tablet, and phone. The Q1 is wired-only, which appeals to enthusiasts who value the lowest possible latency and the simplicity of a single cable, but it is a dealbreaker for anyone who wants a cable-free desk or who types on a tablet in a stand. The Q1 compensates with full QMK/VIA programmability, letting you remap every key, build custom layers, and tweak lighting and macros to a degree the K8 cannot approach. If you want deep customization and the best typing feel, the Q1 wins; if you want wireless freedom and simplicity, the K8 wins.</p>

    <h2 id="price">Price</h2>
    <p>The Keychron K8 starts at $99 for the standard version with a plastic body, and the hot-swap variant costs slightly more. An aluminum-frame version exists for a premium, but the core K8 experience is the $99 plastic model. At that price, it is one of the most affordable ways to get a wireless, hot-swappable, Mac-compatible mechanical keyboard, and its value proposition is strong for first-time mechanical keyboard buyers.</p>

    <p>The Keychron Q1 starts at $149 for the assembled version with Gateron G Pro switches and standard keycaps, with barebones kits available for users who want to supply their own switches and keycaps. The $50 premium over the K8 buys a dramatically better build and typing experience: a solid CNC aluminum case, gasket mounting, sound dampening, hot-swap sockets, and QMK/VIA support. For enthusiasts, the Q1 represents excellent value — comparable custom keyboards from boutique brands often cost $250 or more. For budget buyers who just want a wireless mechanical keyboard, the K8's $99 price remains the more sensible choice. The right call depends on whether you view a keyboard as a basic input device or a long-term typing investment.</p>

    <h2 id="who-wins">Who Wins</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>For typing feel and enthusiast features:</strong> Keychron Q1 wins because its gasket-mounted plate, aluminum case, and sound dampening deliver a softer, deeper, more satisfying typing experience than the K8's tray-mount design.</li>
      <li><strong>For wireless use and multi-device switching:</strong> Keychron K8 wins because its Bluetooth 5.1 with 3-device multipoint lets you switch between a laptop, tablet, and phone instantly, while the Q1 is wired-only.</li>
      <li><strong>For customization and programmability:</strong> Keychron Q1 wins because full QMK/VIA support lets you remap every key and build custom layers, while the K8 offers no programmability.</li>
      <li><strong>For budget buyers:</strong> Keychron K8 wins because at $99 it delivers a wireless, hot-swap-capable mechanical keyboard for $50 less than the Q1.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="recommendation">Final Recommendation</h2>
    <p>If you care about typing feel, build quality, and customization, the Keychron Q1 is the better keyboard and the better long-term investment. Its gasket-mounted aluminum construction produces a typing experience that genuinely justifies the enthusiast hype, and its QMK/VIA programmability means it can grow with you as you discover what you want from a keyboard. At $149, it is one of the best value custom keyboards on the market, and anyone who spends hours a day typing will appreciate the upgrade over a basic mechanical board.</p>

    <p>If you prioritize wireless connectivity, multi-device switching, or a lower price, the Keychron K8 is the right choice. Its Bluetooth multipoint, Mac compatibility, and $99 price make it the best wireless mechanical keyboard for most people, and its hot-swap variant lets you experiment with switches without committing to a soldering iron. For users who type across a laptop, tablet, and phone, or anyone who wants a cable-free desk, the K8's convenience outweighs the Q1's superior typing feel.</p>

    <p>The deciding question is simple: choose the Q1 if you want the best typing experience and customization and do not need wireless; choose the K8 if you want wireless freedom and a lower price. Both are excellent keyboards that punch above their respective price points, and both make a strong case for why Keychron dominates the affordable mechanical keyboard market in 2026.</p>
